[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] A typical Bayesian optimization procedure builds a sequence of evaluation points.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Starting from an initial design $X_{0}$ , the algorithm produces additional evaluation points $x_{1},x_{2},\ldots$ .
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] After n sequential evaluations, $X_{n}=X_{0}\cup \{x_{1},\ldots ,x_{n}\}$ denotes the evaluated points and ${\mathcal {D}}_{n}$ denotes the corresponding observations.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] The next point $x_{n+1}$ , or a batch of points, is selected by optimizing a sampling criterion computed from the current probabilistic model.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Evaluate the objective function, and any constraints if present, at the initial design points.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Construct or update a probabilistic model using the observed data ${\mathcal {D}}_{n}$ .
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Define a sampling criterion, also called an acquisition function or infill criterion, from the probabilistic model.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Optimize the sampling criterion to select $x_{n+1}$ , or a batch of points, for evaluation.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Evaluate the selected point or points and update the data set.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Repeat until an evaluation budget, convergence criterion, or stopping rule is reached.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] The Bayesian strategy treats the unknown objective as a random function and places a prior over it.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] The prior captures assumptions about the behavior of the function.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] After observations are collected, the prior is updated to form a posterior distribution over the objective function.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] The posterior distribution is then used to construct the sampling criterion that determines the next query point.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Bayesian optimization requires a probabilistic model of the unknown objective function and, when present, of unknown constraints.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Given the evaluations observed so far, the model gives a predictive distribution for unevaluated points in the search space.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Sampling criteria are defined from this predictive distribution, so the model provides both predicted objective values and uncertainty estimates.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Such probabilistic models are often called surrogate models or metamodels because they are used in place of direct evaluations of the expensive objective when choosing candidate points.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] Gaussian process regression is the standard probabilistic model in classical presentations of Bayesian optimization and remains common in applications.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/bayesian-optimization] A Gaussian process prior defines a distribution over functions.
