[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] In probability theory and statistics, a **Gaussian process** is a stochastic process (a collection of random variables indexed by time or space), such that every finite collection of those random variables has a multivariate normal distribution.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] The distribution of a Gaussian process is the joint distribution of all those (infinitely many) random variables, and as such, it is a distribution over functions with a continuous domain, e.g. time or space.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] The concept of Gaussian processes is named after Carl Friedrich Gauss because it is based on the notion of the Gaussian distribution (normal distribution).
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes can be seen as an infinite-dimensional generalization of multivariate normal distributions.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are useful in statistical modelling, benefiting from properties inherited from the normal distribution.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] For example, if a random process is modelled as a Gaussian process, the distributions of various derived quantities can be obtained explicitly.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Such quantities include the average value of the process over a range of times and the error in estimating the average using sample values at a small set of times.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] While exact models often scale poorly as the amount of data increases, multiple approximation methods have been developed which often retain good accuracy while drastically reducing computation time.
