[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes can model correlated noise, a specific type of non-Gaussian noise dependent on some underlying unknown distribution correlated with observed values.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] This type of noise is often present in astronomical signals as instrumental systematics or as intrinsic to the observed object as a result of physical processes.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Correlated noise is often a consideration for exoplanet transit events, and Gaussian processes have been used to de-trend these transit light curves (at timescales greater than that of the transit) to allow detection of weaker, more short-lived signals.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] These processes have also been used to disentangle planetary signals from stellar activity indicators inside radial velocity data, another method of exoplanet detection.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Correlated noise produced by active regions on a star's photosphere (as a result of magnetic field interactions) can be of similar timescales as transit events, and Gaussian process models which handle sparsely sampled data are used to confirm exoplanet detections especially around young stars.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] The variability of rotating, magnetically active Sun-like stars can be modeled fairly accurately using Gaussian processes.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] This covariance function allows for the limited but feasible determination of stellar periods as a result of parameter $\lambda _{1}$ but lacks physical information about where these active regions are on the star observed.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Gaussian processes are also used in the analysis of individual and populations of active galactic nuclei (AGNs) due to their stochastic variability in the optical and radio parts of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Damped random walk kernels in particular have previously been used to identify the extent of broad-line emission regions around supermassive black holes using reverberation mapping, and these kernels can also be used to characterize light curve variations for large AGN populations.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Other astrophysical applications of Gaussian processes include models for pulsar timing and dispersion measure, gravitational wave structure and detector uncertainty (notably in the LIGO-Virgo-KAGRA collaboration), transient classification, and quasi-periodic oscillations.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] In practical applications, Gaussian process models are often evaluated on a grid leading to multivariate normal distributions.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Using these models for prediction or parameter estimation using maximum likelihood requires evaluating a multivariate Gaussian density, which involves calculating the determinant and the inverse of the covariance matrix.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] Both of these operations have cubic computational complexity which means that even for grids of modest sizes, both operations can have a prohibitive computational cost.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/gaussian-process] This drawback led to the development of multiple approximation methods.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] In statistics, originally in geostatistics, **kriging** or **Kriging** (/ˈkriːɡɪŋ/), also known as **Gaussian process regression**, is a method of interpolation based on Gaussian process governed by prior covariances.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Under suitable assumptions of the prior, kriging gives the best linear unbiased prediction (BLUP) at unsampled locations.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Interpolating methods based on other criteria such as smoothness (e.g., smoothing spline) may not yield the BLUP.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The method is widely used in the domain of spatial analysis and computer experiments.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The technique is also known as **Wiener–Kolmogorov prediction**, after Norbert Wiener and Andrey Kolmogorov.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The theoretical basis for the method was developed by the French mathematician Georges Matheron in 1960, based on the master's thesis of Danie G.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Krige, the pioneering plotter of distance-weighted average gold grades at the Witwatersrand reef complex in South Africa.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Krige sought to estimate the most likely distribution of gold based on samples from a few boreholes.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The English verb is *to krige*, and the most common noun is *kriging*.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The word is sometimes capitalized as *Kriging* in the literature.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Though computationally intensive in its basic formulation, kriging can be scaled to larger problems using various approximation methods.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Kriging predicts the value of a function at a given point by computing a weighted average of the known values of the function in the neighborhood of the point.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The method is closely related to regression analysis.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Both theories derive a best linear unbiased estimator based on assumptions on covariances, make use of Gauss–Markov theorem to prove independence of the estimate and error, and use very similar formulae.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Even so, they are useful in different frameworks: kriging is made for estimation of a single realization of a random field, while regression models are based on multiple observations of a multivariate data set.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The kriging estimation may also be seen as a spline in a reproducing kernel Hilbert space, with the reproducing kernel given by the covariance function.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The difference with the classical kriging approach is provided by the interpretation: while the spline is motivated by a minimum-norm interpolation based on a Hilbert-space structure, kriging is motivated by an expected squared prediction error based on a stochastic model.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Kriging with *polynomial trend surfaces* is mathematically identical to generalized least squares polynomial curve fitting.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Kriging can also be understood as a form of Bayesian optimization.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Kriging starts with a prior distribution over functions.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] This prior takes the form of a Gaussian process: N samples from a function will be normally distributed, where the covariance between any two samples is the covariance function (or kernel) of the Gaussian process evaluated at the spatial location of two points.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] A set of values is then observed, each value associated with a spatial location.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Now, a new value can be predicted at any new spatial location by combining the Gaussian prior with a Gaussian likelihood function for each of the observed values.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The resulting posterior distribution is also Gaussian, with a mean and covariance that can be simply computed from the observed values, their variance, and the kernel matrix derived from the prior.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] In geostatistical models, sampled data are interpreted as the result of a random process.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] A stochastic process is, in the context of this model, simply a way to approach the set of data collected from the samples.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The first step in geostatistical modulation is to create a random process that best describes the set of observed data.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] A value from location $x_{1}$ (generic denomination of a set of geographic coordinates) is interpreted as a realization $z(x_{1})$ of the random variable $Z(x_{1})$ .
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] In the space A , where the set of samples is dispersed, there are N realizations of the random variables $Z(x_{1}),Z(x_{2}),\ldots ,Z(x_{N})$ , correlated between themselves.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The set of random variables constitutes a random function, of which only one realization is known – the set $z(x_{i})$ of observed data.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] With only one realization of each random variable, it's theoretically impossible to determine any statistical parameter of the individual variables or the function.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The proposed solution in the geostatistical formalism consists in *assuming* various degrees of *stationarity* in the random function, in order to make the inference of some statistic values possible.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The hypothesis of stationarity related to the second moment is defined in the following way: the correlation between two random variables solely depends on the spatial distance between them and is independent of their location.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] In this set, $(i,\;j)$ and $(j,\;i)$ denote the same element.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Generally an "approximate distance" h is used, implemented using a certain tolerance.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] When calculating the weights $w_{i}$ , there are two objectives in the geostatistical formalism: *unbias* and *minimal variance of estimation*.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] If the cloud of real values $Z(x_{0})$ is plotted against the estimated values ${\hat {Z}}(x_{0})$ , the criterion for global unbias, *intrinsic stationarity* or wide sense stationarity of the field, implies that the mean of the estimations must be equal to mean of the real values.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The second criterion says that the mean of the squared deviations ${\big (}{\hat {Z}}(x)-Z(x){\big )}$ must be minimal, which means that when the cloud of estimated values *versus* the cloud real values is more disperse, the estimator is more imprecise.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Depending on the stochastic properties of the random field and the various degrees of stationarity assumed, different methods for calculating the weights can be deduced, i.e. different types of kriging apply.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The unknown value $Z(x_{0})$ is interpreted as a random variable located in $x_{0}$ , as well as the values of neighbors samples $Z(x_{i}),\ i=1,\ldots ,N$ .
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The estimator ${\hat {Z}}(x_{0})$ is also interpreted as a random variable located in $x_{0}$ , a result of the linear combination of variables.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Since the random function is stationary, $E[Z(x_{i})]=E[Z(x_{0})]=m$ , the weights must sum to 1 in order to ensure that the model is unbiased.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Two estimators can have $E[\epsilon (x_{0})]=0$ , but the dispersion around their mean determines the difference between the quality of estimators.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] To find an estimator with minimum variance, we need to minimize $E[\epsilon (x_{0})^{2}]$ .
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] See covariance matrix for a detailed explanation.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Some conclusions can be asserted from this expression.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The additional parameter $\mu$ is a Lagrange multiplier used in the minimization of the kriging error $\sigma _{k}^{2}(x)$ to honor the unbiasedness condition.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Simple kriging is mathematically the simplest, but the least general.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] It assumes the expectation of the random field is known and relies on a covariance function.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] However, in most applications neither the expectation nor the covariance are known beforehand.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The covariance function is a crucial design choice, since it stipulates the properties of the Gaussian process and thereby the behaviour of the model.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] The covariance function encodes information about, for instance, smoothness and periodicity, which is reflected in the estimate produced.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] A very common covariance function is the squared exponential, which heavily favours smooth function estimates.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] For this reason, it can produce poor estimates in many real-world applications, especially when the true underlying function contains discontinuities and rapid changes.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] This is analogous to a linear regression of $Z(x_{0})$ on the other $z_{1},\ldots ,z_{n}$ .
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] which leads to the generalised least-squares version of the Gauss–Markov theorem (Chiles & Delfiner 1999, p.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Although kriging was developed originally for applications in geostatistics, it is a general method of statistical interpolation and can be applied within any discipline to sampled data from random fields that satisfy the appropriate mathematical assumptions.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] It can be used where spatially related data has been collected (in 2-D or 3-D) and estimates of "fill-in" data are desired in the locations (spatial gaps) between the actual measurements.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Another very important and rapidly growing field of application, in engineering, is the interpolation of data coming out as response variables of deterministic computer simulations, e.g. finite element method (FEM) simulations.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] In this case, kriging is used as a metamodeling tool, i.e. a black-box model built over a designed set of computer experiments.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] In many practical engineering problems, such as the design of a metal forming process, a single FEM simulation might be several hours or even a few days long.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] It is therefore more efficient to design and run a limited number of computer simulations, and then use a kriging interpolator to rapidly predict the response in any other design point.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Kriging is therefore used very often as a so-called surrogate model, implemented inside optimization routines.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/kriging] Kriging-based surrogate models may also be used in the case of mixed integer inputs.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] In statistics, **nonlinear regression** is a form of regression analysis in which observational data are modeled by a function which is a nonlinear combination of the model parameters and depends on one or more independent variables.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] The data are fitted by a method of successive approximations (iterations).
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] relates a vector of independent variables, $\mathbf {x}$ , and its associated observed dependent variables, $\mathbf {y}$ .
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] The function f is nonlinear in the components of the vector of parameters $\beta$ , but otherwise arbitrary.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] This function, which is a rectangular hyperbola, is *nonlinear* because it cannot be expressed as a linear combination of the two $\beta$ s.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Systematic error may be present in the independent variables but its treatment is outside the scope of regression analysis.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] If the independent variables are not error-free, this is an errors-in-variables model, also outside this scope.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Other examples of nonlinear functions include exponential functions, logarithmic functions, trigonometric functions, power functions, Gaussian function, and Lorentz distributions.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Some functions, such as the exponential or logarithmic functions, can be transformed so that they are linear.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] When so transformed, standard linear regression can be performed but must be applied with caution.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] See § Linearization §§ Transformation, below, for more details.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] In microbiology and biotechnology, nonlinear regression is used to model complex microbial growth kinetics.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] While simple growth follows monoauxic functions (such as the Gompertz or Boltzmann models), multiphasic (polyauxic) growth is modeled using linear combinations of these nonlinear functions.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] In general, there is no closed-form expression for the best-fitting parameters, as there is in linear regression.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Usually numerical optimization algorithms are applied to determine the best-fitting parameters.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Again in contrast to linear regression, there may be many local minima of the function to be optimized and even the global minimum may produce a biased estimate.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] In practice, estimated values of the parameters are used, in conjunction with the optimization algorithm, to attempt to find the global minimum of a sum of squares.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] For details concerning nonlinear data modeling see least squares and non-linear least squares.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] where $J_{ij}={\frac {\partial f(x_{i},{\boldsymbol {\beta }})}{\partial \beta _{j}}}$ are Jacobian matrix elements.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] ${\hat {\boldsymbol {\beta }}}\approx \mathbf {(J^{T}J)^{-1}J^{T}y} ,$ compare generalized least squares with covariance matrix proportional to the unit matrix.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] The nonlinear regression statistics are computed and used as in linear regression statistics, but using **J** in place of **X** in the formulas.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] The linear approximation introduces bias into the statistics.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Therefore, more caution than usual is required in interpreting statistics derived from a nonlinear model.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] The best-fit curve is often assumed to be that which minimizes the sum of squared residuals.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] This is the ordinary least squares (OLS) approach.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] However, in cases where the dependent variable does not have constant variance, or there are some outliers, a sum of weighted squared residuals may be minimized; see weighted least squares.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Each weight should ideally be equal to the reciprocal of the variance of the observation, or the reciprocal of the dependent variable to some power in the outlier case, but weights may be recomputed on each iteration, in an iteratively weighted least squares algorithm.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Some nonlinear regression problems can be moved to a linear domain by a suitable transformation of the model formulation.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] with parameters *a* and *b* and with multiplicative error term *U*.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] where *u* = ln(*U*), suggesting estimation of the unknown parameters by a linear regression of ln(*y*) on *x*, a computation that does not require iterative optimization.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] However, use of a nonlinear transformation requires caution.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] The influences of the data values will change, as will the error structure of the model and the interpretation of any inferential results.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] On the other hand, depending on what the largest source of error is, a nonlinear transformation may distribute the errors in a Gaussian fashion, so the choice to perform a nonlinear transformation must be informed by modeling considerations.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] of 1/*v* against 1/[*S*] has been much used.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] However, since it is very sensitive to data error and is strongly biased toward fitting the data in a particular range of the independent variable, [*S*], its use is strongly discouraged.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] For error distributions that belong to the exponential family, a link function may be used to transform the parameters under the Generalized linear model framework.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] The *independent* or *explanatory variable* (say X) can be split up into classes or segments and linear regression can be performed per segment.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] Segmented regression with confidence analysis may yield the result that the *dependent* or *response* variable (say Y) behaves differently in the various segments.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/nonlinear-regression] For example, the figure shows that the soil salinity (X) initially exerts no influence on the crop yield (Y) of mustard, until a *critical* or *threshold* value (*breakpoint*), after which the yield is affected negatively.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/radial-basis-function-kernel] In machine learning, the **radial basis function kernel**, or **RBF kernel**, is a popular kernel function used in various kernelized learning algorithms.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/radial-basis-function-kernel] In particular, it is commonly used in support vector machine classification.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/radial-basis-function-kernel] $\textstyle \|\mathbf {x} -\mathbf {x'} \|^{2}$ may be recognized as the squared Euclidean distance between the two feature vectors. $\sigma$ is a free parameter.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/radial-basis-function-kernel] Since the value of the RBF kernel decreases with distance and ranges between zero (in the infinite-distance limit) and one (when **x** = **x'**), it has a ready interpretation as a similarity measure.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/radial-basis-function-kernel] Because support vector machines and other models employing the kernel trick do not scale well to large numbers of training samples or large numbers of features in the input space, several approximations to the RBF kernel (and similar kernels) have been introduced.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/radial-basis-function-kernel] where $\textstyle \varphi$ is the implicit mapping embedded in the RBF kernel.
[src:gaussian-processes-sci/radial-basis-function-kernel] Another approach uses the Nyström method to approximate the eigendecomposition of the Gram matrix *K*, using only a random sample of the training set.
